Inflation in Europe jumped over food
Accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
The November price growth in 13 euro area countries was above expectations, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent registered after 2.6 percent in October, announced by the Luxembourg Union Statistical Office.
The official forecast assumed only 3 percent, reported by Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, British, and Canadian emission banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not reduce the basic interest rate, with reductions resulting in inflation spirals along with rising raw material prices and falling unemployment.
The ECB would like to keep inflation rates below 2%, but close to them.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must "repel" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about this later.
In Germany, November inflation accounts for 3.3 percent of the 15-year record; in Spain it then rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has been thrown up due to rising food and energy prices.
Term prices of wheat have increased by 88 percent, and the soy exchange rate has reached the highest since 1973.
It was also necessary to pay significantly more in 2007 for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets has increased by 52 percent this year, and last month, one barrel of black gold has already cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 percent to 2.5 in 2008 but will fall to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, 12-month inflation will remain approximately 3% over the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to double down interest rates during 2008.
