In many places it is saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due mainly to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hospital health conditions, overcrowding beds, overloading personnel does not help stop diseases, claims the head of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places it is also saved on disinfectants.
In the trauma department of St. John's Hospital, MSA infection was diagnosed recently.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were discovered in a man who entered the hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after that he had to return with an MRSA infection and due to the bacteria found in his organism could not yet be performed one important surgery.
By 10 December this year, 1 094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant agents were reported to the National System of Nesocomialis Surveillance, reported by Karolina Böröczová, the head of the National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant disease agents were definitely registered in hospitals, others are not known.
Almost two-thirds (683) of the infection was caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant gold staphylococci.
A third of the people in the nose without causing disease carry the bacterium Staphylococcusurea (SA).
Infections caused by SA (e. g. cervical inflammation, tonsil inflammation, skin infection, early infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are administered to an excessive degree or inappropriate extent, a bacteria that responds well to antibiotics will develop a bacteria that is very resistant to antibiotics and which spreads rapidly in non-compliant hospital conditions.
Especially if the immune system is temporarily or permanently malfunctioning in patients with a weakened organism, low body weight, or patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, such as early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the head doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are part of daily practice in hospitals.
"The infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the disease agent is not examined."
Resists Antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, treat them with rubber gloves and masks, and we have the antibiotics needed to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined whether the infection is present in their MRSA, however, it is not always possible to avoid infection.
Sampling not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and conditions in domestic hospitals are not favourable for the prevention of the emergence and spread of multi-resistant agents of diseases, claims Karolina Böröczová.
Since this infection is typically found in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should check and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
Microbiological sampling, however, is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
This also involves the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations.
The most cases are thus revealed when the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the primary of the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations for appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for treating individual infections, disease reports.
Antibiotic therapy needs to be targeted, or microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not follow this in all cases.
Sampling of microbiological samples is even rarer in the basic or outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina Böröczová said.
Saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA spreads among patients most often through medical personnel.
That is why hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are serious shortcomings in hospitals as well.
MRSA is transmitted by drip infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients under the conditions of home hospitals.
Rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view patients should be at least 1.5 metres away.
As Karolina Böröczová remarked, unfortunately we can also meet with the fact that in hospitals that are in an adverse material situation, they save on disinfectants, nurses are few and patients are a lot, thereby increasing the chances of developing infections.
According to Karolina Böröczová, where the necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are proven to be less likely or further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has written an MRSA prevention programme or a reduction in its occurrence.
The programme appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a declining trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks among its priorities the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these disease agents.
