Another EUR 400 million for infrastructure
The agreement on three credit frameworks worth EUR 400 million in support of education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy was signed by Minister of Finance János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) in Budapest on Friday.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects implemented by the Cohesion Fund, with the parties having previously entered into a loan agreement of EUR 100 million, the now signed contract covering the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
A loan agreement of EUR 150 million is also used for the budgetary financing of projects related to education.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for these purposes, and the remaining EUR 150 million may be used later, with an extension of the credit agreement.
In the field of innovation, the parties signed a contract of EUR 50 million, which will be used primarily by the budget for the Debrecen University research and development project.
There was also talk about the 4th metro route at the meeting.
The Parties agree that, once Hungary has agreed on the details of the financing of the metro with the EU, it will return to whether and how the original contract needs to be modified.
According to János Veres, this can happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed EUR 8.4 billion in total of 113 projects in Hungary.
