Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard increased the risk of the country
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division (Risk Analysis Division) of the Institute of Political Capital, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the entire region in several respects.
The company's "risk warning" says: in the context of the Hungarian Guard's activities, the greatest political risk is that "a violent ethnic conflict may already occur in the short term" by focusing on the already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Romani population of Hungary.
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is likely to provoke such an action - it is supplied by the Research Institute.
As he writes, all of this can be explained by one of the greatest negligences of Hungarian political leaders: "Public debate on the Roma issue was left to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict. "
This deepens the problem, hinders normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts - the Institute judges.
Moreover, according to the research institute, the Hungarian Guard's activity has "to a large extent ruined the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the belief in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity."
The Institute recalls: part of the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which have become increasingly public since autumn 2006, is that several organizations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007, which are called "national militia" associations.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while they openly proclaim - even armed - the readiness of their members to carry out defence tasks (in the case of natural disasters, domestic assault, disorderly conduct), plus with reference to the inability of the police, military, or state," he adds.
He also notes: all of this is being done in a way that tries to wrap up various political efforts based on the opposition of society to politics and parties to civilian robes.
Thus, emphasising civility and form of society in the case of these groups is not only to avoid legal difficulties of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the Hungarian Guard's activity is also a factor increasing the risk from the perspective of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been pointed out in several neighbouring states as a potential source of danger, the ultranationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries want to apologize for their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the emergence of the Hungarian Guard.
All of this can affect the political stability of the region," he adds.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not an isolated phenomenon, so political risks to the region as a whole have increased.
As he writes, the Hungarian Guard's activity is similar, for example, to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the ultra-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
Against the background of the establishment of the Bulgarian Guard stands the mass Romani riots that broke out in one of Sofia's neighborhoods (Krasna Poljana).
She used that BNU to set up a guard, with the aim of the organization being "national militia."
In the past 17 years, according to her, "Gypsy terror" has occurred in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, reminds the Institute of Political Capital.
