Congress approved the MiFID transfer valid from 1 November
At the same time as the parliamentary negotiations which were concluded today by the vote of Congress on amendments incorporated by the Senate in the bill, the government submitted a public hearing to the regulation that develops the new law in order for both of them to enter into force before the end of the year.
The parties' representatives have highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities needed for the efficient functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial advice services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial services company (ESIS), financial consultancy company (AFI), which is connected to securities companies, securities brokers and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments is increased by connecting multilateral trading and internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets which will compete with current stockbrokers.
Furthermore, the law obliges investment services firms to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure, and risk management processes on the market, and requires a statement of all operations performed to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During the consultation in the Congress Trade Commission, several adjustments were made to ensure that securitised claims were considered to be a "complicated' financial instrument in view of the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what occurred in the USA with high risk mortgage debts (subprime).
Moreover, the transposition of the directive was used to establish legal functions that may be held by Bachelors in the field of economics and corporate governance 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977, which sets out professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require authorisation from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and customer acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
