There is now a dispute over gas prices between Russia and Ukraine, and there is an increased risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of Russia's fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is led by pipelines across Ukraine and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev warned that if Moscow raised gas prices to Ukraine, Russia would be charged higher transit charges.
The previous dispute between these two last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kyiv and Moscow comes when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says he will have to charge Ukraine more, since he has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its deliveries from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," said the Ukrainian economy minister Anatoly Kinach to Reuters.
"The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments concerning the level of transit charges (to Western Europe) through Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This has caused a devastating fall in exports to Western Europe, which has sharply increased prices.
