Scientists reported yesterday that Venus could once have been a pleasant place to live.
Data from an orbiting European station show that the planet is even more like the headstrong twin of the Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit along similar lanes, but Venus is a little closer to the sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and could also be habitable.
But the runaway greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion of solar radiation, and lower rotation rates were sent by Venus after a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is waterless, the temperature on the surface is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by storms and hurricane-power winds.
The findings from the Venus Express European Space Agency probe, which studied the planet for one year, offer a modest view of how the Earth could develop in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the University of Oxford Department of Physics and one of the leading missions of Venus Express said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different than on Earth, even though the planets themselves are quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to compile a scenario in which Venus began as much as the Earth, possibly with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
